      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "299d76a462d0c193",
      "text": "# How great was the great Chatwin?\nThe legendary writer Bruce Chatwin was in search of the bizarre, the wonderful, the strange. Director Werner Herzog has now dedicated a documentary film to the traveler. Younger generations see the Brit more critically. Who is right?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8e02b437b8eb300c",
      "text": "By Carl von Siemens"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f43c87a5984f4d5c",
      "text": "I first learned about the English writer Bruce Chatwin on the day he died. It was one of those January days in Oxford when fog hovered over the snowless gardens and historic courtyards. Students carried their trays into the dining hall of Trinity College and took seats at the brightly polished refectory tables. Half a mile away, the Pitt Rivers Museum's ethnological collection slumbered in its display cases, Noah's Ark as a wooden Biedermeier toy, tattered textiles, brass plates of mermaids from Nigeria."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2c4c843cb8a3665e",
      "text": "\"Bruce Chatwin is dead,\" said a girl in a cuffed blouse, chasing a pea across the table with her fork. \"Who?\", I asked. \"Bruce Chatwin,\" repeated a pale-faced literature student who had announced his coming out a few days earlier, looking at me in disgust, as if it were unforgivable not to know Bruce Chatwin. \"England's most famous travel writer,\" he added tight-lipped. \"He wrote 'Dream Paths.'\""
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "27af473ab3c27710",
      "text": "As I was to find out later, Bruce Chatwin did not like the label \"travel writer\"; but in fact he explored distant lands and struck a chord with his countrymen. \"Almost every writer of my generation in England wanted to be Bruce Chatwin at some time,\" wrote one critic when Dream Paths was published, \"wanted to talk with the same authority as he about Fez and Firdausi, about Nigeria and Nuristan.\""
    },
