    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "33aa432c58066cd7",
      "text": "Thirty years later, the BBC commissions German filmmaker Werner Herzog to make a documentary about Bruce Chatwin. \"Nomad. In the Footsteps of Bruce Chatwin\" takes the title of an older, two-part biopic by Paul Yule and Chatwin's biographer Nicholas Shakespeare and was shown on British television in September 2019. The planned theatrical release the following year fell victim to the pandemic, but now the film is available online, and with mobility and its limitations particularly in the spotlight now, this may be an opportune time to take a look at the filmmaker, the travel writer, and the driven nature that links the two."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7a2947c5d9853bfb",
      "text": "In his notes \"Vom Gehen im Eis,\" Werner Herzog writes: \"A single, all-dominating thought: away from here. The people frighten me. The Eisner woman must not die, she will not die, I will not allow it. She won't die, she won't. Not now, she can't. No, she won't die now, because she won't die. My steps are firm. And now the earth trembles. When I walk, a bison walks. When I rest, a mountain rests.\"\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5ffbb0f008daa176",
      "text": "At the end of November 1974, Herzog learns that film historian Lotte Eisner is dying in Paris. He decides to make a pilgrimage on foot from Munich to her sickbed, thus offering the universe a kind of barter: If he could make it from Munich to Paris on foot, Lotte Eisner would not die. His foot march leads through external as well as internal landscapes, it is a devotion, a prayer to conquer the universe, just as Herzog's hero Fitzcarraldo will later try to make an offer to fate by having a ship pulled over a mountain by indigenous people in the Amazon."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a7c32b51ce1e2619",
      "text": "The prayer is answered, the exertions pay off: When Herzog reaches Paris, Lotte Eisner rises from her sickbed, weak but recovered, someone having announced to her that he would come on foot."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a872ecf6fde0f50d",
      "text": "Bruce Chatwin wrote years later that Werner Herzog was \"the only person with whom I could have a conversation among like-minded people about what I would call the sacred aspect of walking. He and I both believe that walking has not simply therapeutic value, but is a poetic act that can heal the world of its ills.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6075107d2f0da9bc",
      "text": "Chatwin and Herzog met in Australia in 1983, when Chatwin was doing research for \"Dream Paths,\" the book about the wanderings of the Australian aborigines. On the set of \"Fitzcarraldo,\" the German filmmaker had come across a work by Chatwin; he then contacted the author with a request to collaborate on the screenplay of his film \"Where the Green Ants Dream,\" which was also set among the Aborigines. The two met at the Melbourne airport and talked at each other like madmen for two days - it was a marathon of storytelling, Herzog recalls, with Chatwin imitating the people he was telling about and occasionally interrupting his remarks with pointed screams. Later, he read \"Vom Gehen im Eis\" (\"Of Walking in Ice\") and, after reading it, believed Herzog had magical powers; just a few days before his death, he called the bulky German friend to his bedside in Provence.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f94750054389089a",
      "text": "Of course, even Herzog could not cure him, nor could he bring him the death Chatwin asked for, emaciated to the bone. But he did bring \"Wodaabe. The Shepherds of the Sun,\" his new documentary about a nomadic tribe in the Sahara, about pastoral shepherds who walked in rags and at the same time thought they were the most beautiful people in the world."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d57ce492d86a4def",
      "text": "\"The Nomadic Alternative\" was Chatwin's unfinished work, his Moby Dick, which he had pursued across all five continents like Captain Ahab pursues the white whale, and in which he wanted to explore the question of why man is always on the move and does not want to stand still, why he has to move and perhaps only finds happiness in movement. To the sounds of the music Herzog had chosen for his film, an Ave Maria sung in 1902 by Alessandro Moreschi, the last castrato of the Vatican, Bruce Chatwin glides from one faint to the next; [因"
    }
